First, let's find the symmetric difference of A and B (A ∆ B). The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection.

A ∆ B = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9} ∆ {2, 4, 6, 8}
A ∩ B = {} (since A and B have no common elements)
A ∆ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of (A ∆ B) and C.

(A ∆ B) ∆ C = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9} ∆ {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
(A ∆ B) ∩ C = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} (the common elements between A ∆ B and C)

Now, we remove the common elements from the union of (A ∆ B) and C.

(A ∆ B) ∪ C = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9}
(A ∆ B) ∆ C = {6, 7, 8, 9} (after removing the common elements)

So, the symmetric difference of (A ∆ B) ∆ C is {6, 7, 8, 9}.
